gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/I018603/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>
&lt;/p>
&lt;p>Through this research into the politics of accountability surrounding the World Bank and International Monetary Fund?s concessional lending activities, Dr Clegg seeks to clarify our understanding of the ?shareholder? and ?stakeholder? relationships within these arenas of global economic governance.&lt;/p>

&lt;p>&lt;/p>

&lt;p>&amp;nbsp;In relation to shareholder accountability, Dr Clegg shows how, at the Bank, major creditor states have deployed their financial resources to re-frame the organisation?s developmental mandate to focus more tightly on poverty reduction, particularly as measured by the Millennium Development Goals. A parallel process is also uncovered at the Fund, with key creditors employing supplementary finance to push for an understanding of its balance of payments remit that incorporates broader developmental concerns. In relation to stakeholder accountability, Dr Clegg demonstrates that, at both the Bank and Fund, processes of institutional learning have underpinned an increasing acceptance of the operational benefits of building closer relationships with key domestic groups. The evolution of this agenda continues to be shaped by internal debates over the efficacy of such changes, and by contests over resources to embed changed practices.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p>

&lt;p>
&lt;/p>
&lt;p>Working within an economic constructivist framework, Dr Clegg shows how both ideas &lt;em>and&lt;/em> incentives shape the way in which the Bank and Fund operationalise their mandates. These findings contribute to contemporary debates in academic International Relations and International Political Economy, and are of relevance to both policy-makers and non-governmental organisations interested in the work of the World Bank and IMF.&lt;/p>

